Salmon Counts at Bonneville Dam

Corinna Hong

February 18, 2020


Bonneville Lock and Dams first powerhouse was completed in 1938 on the Columbia River in Oregon to provide hydropower to the Pacific Northwest (U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, n.d.). This project visualizes changes in steelhead salmon passage counts across Bonneville Dam from 1940 - 2019. It first looks at changes in daily counts, then changes in monthly and yearly counts over the same time period.

Steelhead in river.
Steelhead Trout (NOAA Fisheries). (n.d.). Retrieved from https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/species/steelhead-trout

# Load packages

# General
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(lubridate)
library(here)
library(paletteer)

# Time Series 
library(tsibble)
library(fable)
library(fabletools)
library(feasts)
library(forecast)
# Read in data

salmon <- read_csv("cbr_fish_passage_bonneville_allyrs_steelhead.csv") %>% 
  clean_names()
# Wrangle data for daily counts

salmon_day <- salmon %>%
  unite(year, mm_dd, col = "date", sep = "-") %>% # unite year and mmdd column and selarate the values with "-"
  mutate(yr_mo_day = lubridate::parse_date_time(date, "ydm")) %>% # formate date
  drop_na(yr_mo_day, value) # drop NAs from value column
# Create graph of daily counts

salmon_day_gg <- ggplot(data = salmon_day, aes(x = yr_mo_day, y = value)) +
  geom_line(color = "forestgreen") +
  labs (x = "Year", y = "Count") +
  scale_y_continuous() +
  theme_minimal()

salmon_day_gg

Figure 1. Daily Steelhead Salmon Passage at Bonneville Dam (1940 - 2019). Time-seris plot showing daily changes in steelhead salmon counts at Bonneville Dam. Data accessed at: http://www.cbr.washington.edu/dart/query/adult_graph_text 

# Wrangle data for monthly counts

salmon_parse <- salmon_day %>% 
  mutate(month = month(yr_mo_day, label = TRUE)) %>% # oull month from yr_mo_day, label = true gives months 3 letter label
  mutate(year = year(yr_mo_day))

salmon_monthly <- salmon_parse %>% 
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarize(total = sum(value))


salmon_monthly$year <- as.character(salmon_monthly$year) # Transform month from continuous to categorical (so legend in graph is not a gradient)
# Graph data for monthly counts

salmon_month_gg <- ggplot(salmon_monthly, aes(x = month, y = total, group = year)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year)) +
  labs (x = "Month", y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_paletteer_c("harrypotter::gryffindor") +
  scale_y_continuous() +
  theme_minimal()

salmon_month_gg # FIX THIS GRAPH

Figure 2. Monthly Steelhead Salmon Passage at Bonneville Dam (1940 - 2019). Time-seris plot showing monthly changes in steelhead salmon counts at Bonneville Dam. Counts were totaled by month for each year. Data accessed at: http://www.cbr.washington.edu/dart/query/adult_graph_text 

# Wrangle data for yearly counts

salmon_yearly <- salmon_parse %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(total = sum(value))
# Graph data for yearly counts

salmon_year_gg <- ggplot(salmon_yearly, aes(x = year, y = total)) +
  geom_line(color = "forestgreen") +
  labs (x = "Year", y = "Count") +
  scale_y_continuous() +
  theme_minimal()

salmon_year_gg

Figure 3. Yearly Steelhead Salmon Passage at Bonneville Dam (1940 - 2019). Time-seris plot showing daily changes in steelhead salmon counts at Bonneville Dam. Counts were totaled by year. Data accessed at: http://www.cbr.washington.edu/dart/query/adult_graph_text
